title: For Sale:  HECKLER & KOCH VP9 STRIKER FIRE LEM 15RD SAO 2 15rd Magazines M700009-A5
postcontent: The VP9 is Heckler & Koch’s latest handgun and the first striker fired HK since the renowned P7 series pistols were introduced in the 1980s. Experience gained by HK engineers with the recent P30 pistol had a direct influence on the design of the VP9, but the VP9 breaks new ground with its integration of a unique striker firing system with an enhanced HK light pull trigger. The net result is trigger quality unequaled in any production striker fired handgun.HK pioneered the first striker fired handguns, producing both the VP70 and P7 series, designs that impacted several models by HK competitors. But a superior trigger has eluded most striker fired pistol designs. The VP9 trigger surpasses those found on competitors. It has a short, light take-up with a solid, single action type break followed by a short positive reset.The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall crisp break. Typically striker fired guns have a pre travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. The VP9 you have a less than noticeable pre travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break.The VP9 uses HK’s ergonomic handgun grip design that includes three changeable back straps and six side panels accommodating all hand sizes. Molded finger grooves in the front of the pistol’s grip also instinctively position an operator’s hand for optimal shooting. Only HK handguns have such a customized grip.Although influenced by other HK models, the VP9 has all the hallmarks of the latest state of the art handgun. All controls are completely ambidextrous. Slide releases are present on both sides of the frame and the magazine release can be easily activated by left or right handed shooters.A new feature is HK’s patented charging supports simple components that are mounted on each side of the rear of the slide and provide better gripping leverage for racking the slide rearward. The charging supports speed reloading and make operating the VP9 easier for shooters with reduced hand strength. The VP pistols uses the proven P30 steel magazine 15 and 10 round capacity available.The VP9 has an extended Picatinny MIL STD-1913 rail molded into its polymer frame for mounting lights and accessories.The VP9’s proprietary captive flat recoil spring helps reduce the recoil forces effecting the operator and the handgun, improving shooter control during rapid firing and prolonging component service life.HK’s famous cold hammer forged barrel made from cannon grade steel ensures long service life. Similar HK barrels on 9 mm P30 models have fired more than 90,000 rounds in endurance tests in 2010. The polygonal bore profile, with no traditional lands-and-grooves rifling, contributes to longer service life as well as a slight increase in muzzle velocity.The VP9’s machined steel slide is protected from corrosion and wear by HK’s hostile environment finish and all metal components including springs and pins have superior metallurgy.VP pistols are made in Heckler & Koch’s Oberndorf factory in southwest Germany. The VP9 is well-suited for civilian sport shooting, security, military, and law enforcement use.Covered by Heckler & Koch’s limited lifetime warranty, the HK VP9 is a solid design engineered with the famous long-term durability that make HK products especially cost-effective when subjected to total life cycle cost analysis. postcontent: Seller Stock #: LG54169TU Photos are generic, but buyers will receive a virtually identical shotgun. Dealers, Departments, and Collectors, however, may take any number of extra very similar specimens of the same variant we might have on hand at the same per-gun price and with no additional shipping charges. The Mossberg model 500 has never been as prestigious as the arch-competitor Remington 870, but it’s just as tried, and just as true. Here is a close descendant to the first Mossberg 500 riot guns that saw increasing action in the United States beginning in 1964. Manufacturer, of course, is O.F. Mossberg & Sons of New Haven, CT. Model is 500, All Purpose series; factory sku is 54169 or thereabouts. Type is pump or slide action shotgun. Construction is steel barrel, magazine tube, double slide bars, bolt, trigger and internal parts all built into an alloy receiver that undercuts the 870 on weight. Stock and forend are satin finished American Hardwood with cut checkering on the semi beavertail forend’s underside, and matching pattern to the buttstock pistol grip area laterals. Metal finish is blued steel with semi gloss black anodized receiver. Trigger group housing is high impact black polymer, with .292 gold plated smooth faced steel combat trigger. Safety is top tang type. Barrel is 3 inch chambered 18 1/2 inch matte blue steel plain bead sight, with .730 vicinity Cylinder Bore muzzle. We have added a black polymer heat shield reminiscent of the Winchester Model 12s in action beside the Mossbergs. Magazine capacity is 5 rounds of 2 3/4 inch shells, or 4 rounds of 3 inch shells, 5+1 capacity on 2 3/4 inch shells. Weight empty is 6 3/4 pounds, with center of gravity at the breech. Buttstock measures 13 7/8 inches from the trigger face to the end of the 7/8 inch black rubber factory recoil pad. Stock drop is 1 1/2 inches at the comb, and 2 1/2 inches at the butt, with a right hand cant of about 3/4 inch. All 500 receivers are drilled to accept a Weaver # 88 or 417 series 4 screw optics base. Photo specimen and its mates are what we call factory demos. It served as showgirl for Mossberg’s sales force, on the road with their reps and writers; and at gun industry trade shows like the annual SHOT show in Las Vegas. Surface detractions are minimal, really no more streaking and faint edge whitening than what one sees on lots of new display guns in stores. We rate it as Excellent, 90 to 95 percent vicinity by our estimate. Shoppers can possibly spot the letter U stamped on the left side of the receiver above the serial number. Bore, chamber, and mechanism are all bright and clean. Each 500 custom riot gun comes in a relabeled Mossberg Factory Box with factory lock, and instruction manual that contains Mossberg’s warranty statement. If this shotgun was test fired, it was fewer than 20 times. Replacement pricing on mossberg com was well over $400. title: For Sale:  Phillipine Slamfire “Guerrilla Gun”
postcontent: Slamfire “Guerrilla Gun”, one of several hundred improvised shot guns that were hand fashioned using pipes, wood, sheet metal and nails. Dating from 1942-43, under the leadership of Lt. Iliff Richardson, USN these weapons were first made in a small shop in the jungle on the island of Leyte to arm the local resistance against Japanese invaders. In an effort to acquire real rifles, pistols, grenades, ammo and other useful military items the guerrilla forces utilized these guns to shoot Japanese soldiers from ambush. By this method they ultimately armed an effective and organized fighting force that assisted the Allied forces in driving the Japanese from the Phillipines. There is a wealth of information online about Richardson and the guerrilla guns.This 12ga. Slamfire shotgun is complete with a weatherproof tag attached to it that indicates it's provenance. It reads; Presented to Master Sgt. George Gasda.Moro Gun “Paliuntod”Secured from Moros at CotabatoIsland of Mindenao, P.I. I-938.Adrian R. Brian, Lt. Col. Infantry.Here is an opportunity to own an authentic piece of WW II history. $750.00 includes S/H
